        "answer_count": 1,
        "title": "Using log4j2 Configuration name in the RollingFileAppender&#39;s fileName",
        "body": "<p>In the log4j2 examples, some configurations have names:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;Configuration status=\"debug\" strict=\"true\" name=\"MyApplication1\"\n           packages=\"org.apache.logging.log4j.test\"&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I would like to use this name in the filename pattern for RollingFileAppender:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;RollingFile name=\"File\" fileName=\"/user/home/abc/${ctx:name}.log\"&gt;...&lt;/RollingFile&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Unfortunately, \"${ctx:name}\" doesn't make sense to log4j, neither do \"${name}\" nor \"${log4j:name}\", so I was wondering if I could get the Configuration name at all for this purpose...<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 48586274,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "log4j2"
        ],
        "score": 0,
        "is_answered": false,
        "view_count": 125
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [{
        "owner": {
            "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/816327571e74d2518fa5d5feeb6be737?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
            "account_id": 8598286,
            "user_type": "registered",
            "user_id": 6440704,
            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6440704/anton-balaniuc",
            "reputation": 11847,
            "display_name": "Anton Balaniuc"
        },
        "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
        "score": 0,
        "is_accepted": false,
        "last_activity_date": 1517587741,
        "creation_date": 1517587741,
        "body": "<p>you can add it to <code>Properties<\/code> section<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;Configuration status=\"debug\" name=\"app-config\" packages=\"org.apache.logging.log4j.test\"&gt;\n&lt;Properties&gt;\n   &lt;Property name=\"filename\"&gt;app-file&lt;/Property&gt;\n&lt;/Properties&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and use it later on <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;RollingFile name=\"File\" fileName=\"/user/home/abc/${filename}.log\"&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
